{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488664"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"505"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/505"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.62,0.31,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31717"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/505"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1322"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42091"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31717"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man attends his GP clinic to discuss some nodules on his back. These started appearing about six years ago and have been slowly increasing in number (image). They do not bother him unduly but sometimes they cause mild irritation. He does not have any other health issues. On examination there are numerous, well-demarcated skin-coloured papules and nodules on the back that are non-tender, on palpation the lesion is retracting and reappears on the release of pressure, there are also 6-7, dark coloured macules measuring 20-30mm in diameter. There are also 3-4 bilateral freckles in the axillary region. A biopsy of the lesion showed the lesion made up of mixed cells, elongated spindle-shaped cells as well as pleomorphic fibroblast-like cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Schwannomas","Neurofibromatosis","Dermatofibromas","Legius syndrome","Superficial leiomyoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lesions in this scenario along with other signs are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurofibromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E. Schwannomas are made up of mixed cell types, not a single cell type and this is consistent with the findings of the biopsy of the lesion. The lesions showed in the image are neurofibromas which are painless, skin-coloured, well-demarcated papules and nodules. Buttonhole sign (lesions retracting on pressure and reappearing on the release of pressure) is also positive which is an indication of neurofibromatosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurofibromatosis type 1 is an autosomal-dominant genetic disorder that affects all the offspring of an affected individual. The incidence of neurofibromatosis type 1 is noted to be 1 in 2600 to 3000 individuals. There is no predilection for the male or female gender. Fifty percent of the presentations are familial, while the rest of the cases are sporadic. Diagnosis of neurofibromatosis includes the presence of two or more of the following features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESix or more cafe-au-lait spots, greater than 5 mm prepubertal and greater than 15 mm post-pubertal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo or more neurofibromas or one or more plexiform neurofibroma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAxillary or groin freckling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOptic glioma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo or more Lisch nodules\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESphenoid dysplasia, dysplasia or thinning of long bone cortex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst-degree relative with neurofibromatosis type 1\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOut of these, the patient in this scenario meets three criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchwannoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign peripheral nerve sheath tumour comprised predominantly of Schwann cells. Associated with somatic and germline mutations in NF2. Histologically often more cellular, and circumscribed, with Verocay bodies and Antoni A and B areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign proliferation of fibroblasts and histiocytes within the dermis. Often presents as an indurated papule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial leiomyoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign dermal smooth muscle neoplasm, often arising from arrector pili (pilo-leiomyoma).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeigus syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the presence of cafe-au-lait spots without the presence of neurofibromas. For the diagnosis of leigus syndrome, at least two points from the following criteria should be met:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFive or more caf\u00e9 au lait macules bilaterally distributed and no other neurofibromatosis type 1 related diagnostic criteria except for axillary or inguinal freckling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA heterozygous pathogenic (or likely pathogenic) variant in SPRED1 in 100% of cells from unaffected tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA parent with the diagnosis of Legius syndrome by the above criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neurofibromatosis type 1 presents with cafe-au-lait spots, neurofibromas and axillary/inguinal freckles."],"references":["Le C, Bedocs PM. Neurofibromatosis. [Updated 2022 Apr 9]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Messersmith L, Krauland K. Neurofibroma. [Updated 2022 Aug 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17473"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"505"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18911"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18911"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8eaf111-30d2-41f8-905a-da540824dfc8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8eaf111-30d2-41f8-905a-da540824dfc8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":387,"height":516}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17473"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-20T18:14:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-01-20T18:14:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"505"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31717"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6